## Determine the cash flow at the moment of the merger (current cash flow)

To calculate the current cash flow or the cash flow at the moment of the merger we have two factors to determine: 

- Cost of the acquisition.

The total price birdie should pay considering the $8$ million outstanding shares it has. 
$$
\begin{align*}
\text{Total price of merger} &= \text{Merger price per share}\times\text{Number of shares outstanding}\\[10pt]
&= \$23.13\times 8,000,000 \text{ shares}\\[10pt]
&= \$ 185,040,000
\end{align*}
$$
- The value of company $B$ to company $A$. this value expresses the amount company $A$ would receive if the merger occurs. Now, is been declared that if Birdie Golf buys Hybrid Golf, an immediate dividend of $\$55$ million would be paid from Hybrid Golf to Birdie. We consider this the value of firm $B$ (Hybrid) to firm $A$ (Birdie). 

We can now say that the current cash flow is: 
$$
\begin{align*}
\text{Current cash flow} &= 
\begin{array}{c}
\text{Value Company $A$}\\ 
\text{receives after merger}
\end{array}
 - 
\begin{array}{c}
\text{Cost to Firm $A$}\\ 
\text{of the acquisition}
\end{array}
\\[10pt]
&= \$55,000,000 - \$ 185,040,000\\[10pt]
&= -\$130,040,000.
\end{align*}
$$
